wish Polish neighbors. A previously untold story of the complicity of non-Germans in the extermination of the Jews, Neighbors shows how people victimized by the Nazis could at the same time victimize their Jewish fellow citizens. In a new preface, Gross reflects on the book’s explosive international impact and the backlash it continues to provoke from right-wing Polish nationalists who still deny their ancestors’ role in the destruction of the Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnic relations. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandzJedwabne. 0aJedwabne Massacre, Jedwabne, Poland, 1941. 0aJewszPolandzJedwabnexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCollaborationistszPolandzJedwabne. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aActivism.  aAdolf Hitler.  aAntipathy.  aAntony Polonsky.  aAttempt.  aAuthorities (V franchise).  aAuxiliary police.  aBelarus.  aBiebrza.  aBig lie.  aBlackmail.  aBolsheviks.  aBusybody.  aChairman.  aCollective identity.  aComparison of Nazism and Stalinism.  aCulprit.  aDemoralization (warfare).  aDenazification.  aDeportation.  aDisgust.  aDocumentary film.  aEnthusiasm.  aExplanation.  aFellow traveller.  aFestschrift.  aFig leaf.  aFrom Time Immemorial.  aGalician Jews.  aGermans.  aGestapo.  aGleichschaltung.  aHebrew literature.  aHis Family.  aHistoriography.  aJedwabne.  aJewish Historical Institute.  aJews.  aLiterary criticism.  aLocal community.  aLumpenproletariat.  aMass murder.  aMechanic.  aMental reservation.  aMilitary occupation.  aMinsk.  aModus operandi.  aMolotov–Ribbentrop Pact.  aMrs.  aNKVD.  aNational-Democratic Party (Poland).  aNationality.  aNazi Germany.  aNazi Party.  aNazism.  aNeumark.  aNeutron bomb.  aPeasant. 